article.description:
Jason Richardson returned from an ankle injury to
score 32 points Friday night in Golden State's 108-95 victory over the Houston Rockets.
article.headline: Warriors record rare road victory against Rockets
article.linkText: Richardson's return sparks Warriors past Hornets
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Jason Richardson wasn't all that was driving the Houston Rockets batty Friday night. After a bat got loose and strafed the floor for five minutes as play was suspended in the second quarter, the Golden State guard proved more difficult to catch despite missing his last two games with a left ankle sprain. He finished with 32 points in a 108-95 Golden State victory. "It just happened," the rookie said. "It's not like I'm trying to go out there and (only) score points." Richardson was injured March 1 and missed the next two games, but he showed few ill effects in his 36 minutes. "I wasn't sure what to expect, but he had practiced the last two days and he looked good," coach Brian Winters said. "It was an excellent performance from him." The Rockets had much less success containing Richardson than the bat, which began its antics by buzzing Rockets guard Moochie Norris before eventually being netted by a Houston ballboy during a timeout promotion in which some children were shooting baskets. "This happened to us in San Antonio," Richardson said, referring to a game earlier this week where a bat also made it on the court. "Maybe the bats are following us." The ballboy released the bat unharmed outside the arena. Unfortunately for the Rockets, they couldn't do the same with Richardson or teammate Antawn Jamison, who added 27 points for Golden State, which snapped a 13-game road losing streak. After Houston narrowed Golden State's lead to 89-87 with 6:17 left, Richardson's jumper started a 11-2 run for the Warriors, whose last previous road victory was Dec. 22 at Denver. Richardson and Jamison combined for all the points during Golden State's game-sealing stretch. Danny Fortson had 18 rebounds for the Warriors. Norris said Richardson demanded more defensive attention than he got. "He and Cuttino were having a real battle out there," Norris said. "But as a team, we need to help slow him down, and we didn't." Richardson was 10-for-11 from the foul line, mirroring his team's night. "It's very hard to win when we don't shoot the ball well and the other team gets 33 free throws and makes 29," Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. Houston was correspondingly cold from the 3-point line, sinking just 4 of 27. Cuttino Mobley led Houston with 31 points, followed by Steve Francis with 23. Francis fouled out in the final minute as the Rockets unsuccessfully tried to rally. "They outhustled us and outrebounded us," Francis said, referring to Golden State's 58-45 advantage on the boards. "We just couldn't get the stops on them in the fourth quarter." Some of the Warriors theorized the Rockets were dragging toward the end after playing the night before in a 99-97 loss at San Antonio. Winters had little sympathy. "That's life in the NBA," he said. "I thought we defended well and got the stops in the fourth quarter." Mobley dominated the first quarter, scoring 16 of Houston's 26 points, but the Rockets still trailed by two. Golden State led 56-54 at halftime and led by as many as 13 during the third quarter before Houston, led by Francis' 14 in the period, scrapped back. Game notes
The Rockets are 22-24 excluding their NBA-high 15-game losing streak earlier this season. ... Before the game, Golden State activated forward Chris Mills, who missed nine games with a right ankle injury. Reserve forward Cedric Henderson was deactivated because of left knee tendinitis. ... The Warriors are 4-19 in their last 23 games against the Rockets.
